'''Tete Owen Yengi''' (born 28 November 2000) is an Australian professional [[association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]] for [[J1 League]] club [[FC Machida Zelvia|Machida Zelvia]], on loan from {{Scottish football updater|Livingst}} club [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]], and the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia national team]]. Yengi has previously played for [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]], [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], [[Vaasan Palloseura|VPS]], [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] and [[Kuopion Palloseura|KuPS]].

==Club career==
===Newcastle Jets===
After playing two seasons at a semi-pro level with [[Adelaide Comets FC|Adelaide Comets]] in [[National Premier Leagues South Australia|NPL SA]], Yengi signed a scholarship deal with Australian top division side [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]] on 30 December 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://newcastlejetsfc.com.au/news/a-league-yengi-and-armson-sign-scholarship-deals |title=Yengi and Armson sign scholarship deals |access-date=2022-04-06 |website=newcastlejetsfc.com.au |date=30 December 2020 |publisher=Newcastle Jets FC |orig-date=30 December 2020}}</ref> He made a total of nine appearances in [[A-League Men|A-League]] during the [[2020–21 A-League|2020–21]] season.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Paquette|first=Catherine|date=28 September 2021|title=Newcastle Jets A-League Attacker Becomes Second Aussie at Ipswich Town|url=https://www.ftbl.com.au/news/newcastle-jets-a-league-attacker-becomes-second-aussie-at-ipswich-town-570446|access-date=29 September 2021|website=FTBL}}</ref>

===Ipswich Town and loans===
In September 2021, Yengi moved to England and signed for [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on a one-year deal with the option for a further year, initially joining the team's Under 23 side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2021/september/tete-yang-named-on-bench-for-u23s/ |title=New arrival Yengi on bench for U23s |publisher=Ipswich Town FC |date=27 September 2021 |accessdate=6 April 2022}}</ref>

====VPS (loan)====
In April 2022, Yengi joined [[Vaasan Palloseura]] (VPS) on loan for the [[2022 Veikkausliiga|2022 season]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://vepsu.fi/uutinen/tete-yengi-vepsuun |title=Tete Yengi Vepsuun! |access-date=2022-04-06 |website=vepsu.fi |date=6 April 2022 |orig-date=6 April 2022 |language=finnish}}</ref> During his time in Finland, Yengi scored seven goals and assisted a further eleven in [[Veikkausliiga]], winning his club's Player of the Year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/sport/23115937.ipswich-town-tete-yengi-named-player-year-finland/|title=Ipswich Town: Tete Yengi named Player of Year in Finland|publisher=East Anglian Daily Times|last1=Watson|first1=Stuart|date=10 November 2022|accessdate=31 January 2023}}</ref>

====Northampton Town (loan)====
On 31 January 2023, Yengi signed a new eighteen-month contract and subsequently joined [[EFL League Two|League Two]] club [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ntfc.co.uk/news/2023/january/tete_yengi/|title=Northampton Town Sign Tete Yangi on Loan From Ipswich Town|website=www.ntfc.co.uk|date=31 January 2023|accessdate=31 January 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2023/january/new-contract-for-tete-yengi-and-loan-move-to-northampton/|title=New Deal and Cobblers Loan for Tete|website=www.itfc.co.uk|date=31 January 2023|accessdate=31 January 2023}}</ref>

====KuPS (loan)====
On 16 July 2023, Yengi returned to Finland and signed a loan deal with [[Kuopion Palloseura]] (KuPS) for the remainder of the [[2023 Veikkausliiga|2023]] season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kups.fi/tervetuloa-keltamustiin-tete-yengi/ |title=Tervetuloa Keltamustiin Tete Yengi|date=16 July 2023 |publisher=kups.fi |orig-date=16 July 2023}}</ref>

===Livingston===
On 1 January 2024, a [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] announced the signing of Yengi on a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Livingston sign Australian striker Tete Yengi from Ipswich Town |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67850698 |language=en|date=1 January 2024|access-date=1 January 2024}}</ref>
Yengi made his debut the following day in a 1-2 home defeat against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] and scored his first Livi goal in the next league match, a penalty in a 1-4 home defeat by [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]. He added a further three league goals, opening the scoring on each occasion, in a 1-0 home win against St Mirren, a 1-3 home defeat by [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] and a 5-1 loss away to [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Aberdeen 5-1 Livingston: Dons continue fine form by punishing Livi |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11781/13135226/aberdeen-5-1-livingston-dons-continue-fine-form-by-punishing-livi |website=Sky Sports |access-date=9 June 2025}}</ref> Despite Yengi's four goals in 16 games, at the end of the 2024-25 season, Livingston were relegated to the Scottish Championship after finishing bottom of the Premiership. In the Scottish Cup, Yengi added two memorable goals to his tally. Firstly in the fifth round, he headed home a 120th minute winner in a tie away to Partick Thistle, before equalizing to make the score 2-2 in an eventual 4-2 sixth round away defeat against Premiership champions Celtic at Celtic Park.<ref>{{cite web |title=Celtic 4-2 Livingston |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68460886 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=9 June 2025}}</ref>

In the [[2024-25 Livingston F.C. season|2024-25 season]] Yengi competed with [[Stevie May]] and [[Robbie Muirhead]] for a place in the team, starting the fewest matches of the three, but played 42 times across all competitions and scored 10 goals. Notably he scored in the [[2024-25 Scottish Challenge Cup|Scottish Challenge Cup]] final, a 5-0 win over [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]], and in the second-leg of the [[2024–25_Scottish_Premiership#Premiership_play-offs|Premiership Play-off final]], a 2-4 victory against Ross County to seal promotion back to the top flight.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen's Park vs Livingston: SPFL Trust Trophy final |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cz03vzdrgmpt |website=BBC Sport |access-date=9 June 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ross County 2-4 Livingston (3-5 agg) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cpd41v9p65xt |website=BBC Sport |access-date=9 June 2025}}</ref>

==== Machida Zelvia (loan) ====
On 28 January 2026, Yengi moved to [[J1 League]] side [[FC Machida Zelvia|Machida Zelvia]] on loan until 30 June 2026, with an option to buy.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Black |first=Dave |date=2026-01-28 |title=Squad Update {{!}} Yengi heads to Japan on loan |url=https://livingstonfc.co.uk/squad-update-yengi-heads-to-japan-on-loan/ |access-date=2026-01-28 |website=Livingston FC |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 17 April 2026, Yengi scored the only goal of the game in a 1-0 win vs [[Al-Ittihad_Club_(Jeddah)|Al Ittihad]] in the [[AFC Champions League]] Quarter-Final.{{Citation needed|date=May 2026}}

==International career==
Yengi was named in the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]]'s 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], despite never having been capped at international level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cdxp53k7qv1o|title=World Cup 2026: Uncapped Tete Yengi and Cristian Volpato make Australia squad|date=31 May 2026|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0RCcBgN3c5w|title=Tete Yengi: It's a great feeling to be here with the CommBank Socceroos &#124; Press Conference|author=Football Australia|date=1 June 2026|via=YouTube}}</ref>

Yengi scored the equalising goal on international debut in a friendly against Switzerland on June 6, 2026 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/report/_/gameId/401869743|title=Socceroos draw with Swiss in final World Cup warm-up|date=6 June 2026|website=ESPN}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Yengi is of South Sudanese and English descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://keepup.com.au/news/a-generation-that-can-change-the-view-of-millions-of-australians/|title=Special feature: The record cohort giving 'millions of us' a new perspective on Australia|date=16 January 2022}}</ref> His older brother, [[Kusini Yengi|Kusini]], also plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] in the [[J1 League]], at [[Cerezo Osaka]] on loan from [[Scottish Premiership]] side [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].<ref name=cp/><ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-01-29 |title=Aberdeen's Kusini Yengi goes on loan to Japan |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c2e1ynn3m27o |access-date=2026-02-08 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

